text.text: Nam NGUYEN commented on this

In 19 years, the value of my time skyrocketed from 134/hour at 25 to 2,00,000/hour at 44.

All thanks to *one* thing.

In 2005, I was earning 2.78L a year  about 134/hour.

But I didnt have the skills, exposure, or network to increase the value of my time.

So in 2006, I made the biggest investment of my life:
I bet on myself.

I went for an MBA from ISB, taking a HUGE loan with no collateral backing.

I got better opportunities.
My compensation kept rising.

Today, I work for less than 20hrs a week, own 100% of a company that earns 27Cr a year, generating a profit of >5Cr.

That one decision changed everything.
It taught me a lesson Ive seen play out again and again:

Self-investment is the ONLY asset that can consistently deliver extraordinary returns.

There is enough content out there that shows you how investing in stocks, gold, crypto, etc., will make you a millionaire.

All of them are not lying.
It's mathematically possible.

But practically, your personal growth will always be a leading indicator of your financial growth.

Our family was in financial debt in 2005, when I decided to add a 14L education loan to our loan portfolio.

I am glad I took the bet.
And I am grateful that it worked out.

description.text: Analyst at Ministry of Justice UK | MSc at Oxford | London School of Economics Graduate
description.accessibilityText: Analyst at Ministry of Justice UK | MSc at Oxford | London School of Economics Graduate

subDescription.accessibilityText: 5 days ago  Edited  Visible to anyone on or off LinkedIn

text.text: Nam NGUYEN commented on this

I graduated from LSE in 2023. All smiles on graduation day, but I had cried my eyes out the night before.

On results day, I received a 2.2 on my dissertation. I wasnt devastated by the grade itself. What broke me was how much love and thought Id poured into that piece of work. I had been so excited to pursue it further for my masters. In that moment, I felt like an imposter. I knew what that grade would mean for my future applications, for my confidence, and for the plans Id dreamed up for so long.

I couldnt understand how my dissertation, the project Id cherished the most, could be worth a 2.2. I would wake up in the middle of the night, crying. My mum would say, No ones hard work goes to waste. If youve met your Oxford offer, thats what matters. My dad told me to fight it. I wanted to believe them, but deep down, I felt like the verdict had already been written.

I lodged a complaint, appealed, sent thousands of emails over the next two years.  It became bed time routine. LSE admitted that the dissertation hadnt been marked according to the usual process due to the Marking and Assessment Boycott, but still stood by the grade. I asked questions: Was there a second marker? Was there any moderation? Eventually, they offered me 200 and an NDA but refused a remark. An academic even said no one else has complained so this case doesnt stand. 

I took my case to the Office of the Independent Adjudicator. They listened. They asked LSE to re-mark my dissertation.

Today, I received a corrected transcript. The 57 has become a 72: a First Class. Ive also been awarded the David Piachaud Prize for conspicuous performance. 

So if youre reading this: please dont let any organisation define whats enough for you. Dont let a grade define you, because, sometimes, even that can be redefined. 

For two years, I struggled to even start my thesis at Oxford because I believed I had barely passed once after years of working for it, what if I failed again? Shyed away from publishing my reports at work. I let that one number decide my worth. I shouldnt have. But I didnt know better. Now I do.

Whether or not I engage further with LSE depends on how they respond. But Ive come this far. Becoming my lawyer, writing appeals, finishing a masters, all while carrying the weight of that past, it seemed as if a string was untied. 

And finally, to every person who stood by me during this time, thank you. I only share this because I know how many of us have looked at a grade and felt our world collapse. But please believe me when I say: fight for things you believe in! I would love to pass on the lessons and knowledge Ive collected through this experience its worthless if left unshared so if I can help you, please reach out!

And if you are affiliated with any institution in any capacity, our teachers need to be respected with better working conditions and better pay always thinking about them!!!!

I appreciate the hustle, but this is not way.

"Could you please answer?"

It feels desperate and needy.

I have no context.

I get it, it's really tough out there.

I'm out here in the trenches like everyone else.

But come on folks, we can do better.


Proper follow-up should either add context (why them and why now) or point to the next step in the cadence.

Example 1:

"Figured since (trigger event- like recent hiring in a certian dept), X might be a challenge right now. Could be I'm way off here though.😅"


Example 2:

"Gonna try and catch you over the phone tomorrow, hope to speak then ."

Follow up is where the gold is, give it the attention it deserves.



P.S. I know emojis aren't for everyone. I totally dig them, but you do you.

subDescription.accessibilityText: 4 days ago  Visible to anyone on or off LinkedIn

text.text: Nam NGUYEN commented on this

18 years without a boss taught me this about freedom:

It's not what you think it is.

When I first quit, I thought freedom meant:

 Sleeping in
 Working whenever
 Zero accountability
 Doing whatever I wanted

Classic rookie mistake.

Here's what happened:

Year 1: I worked MORE than I ever did with a boss.

Because when no one's watching, you either step up or starve.

Year 3: I burned out harder than any corporate job could have done.

Because I hadn't learned the difference between freedom FROM and freedom TO.

Year 5: I finally got it.

Freedom isn't the absence of structure.

It's the ability to build your own.

Most people quit their jobs and become their own worst boss.

 They hustle 24/7
 They never take breaks
 They measure worth by hours worked
 They create a prison with invisible bars

Sound familiar?

Here's what real freedom looks like:

 Saying no to good opportunities because they're not great ones
 Working 15 hours when you're inspired, 3 when you're not
 Choosing clients who energize rather than drain
 Building systems that work without you

But the biggest lesson?

Freedom is internal first, external second.

You can have all the money, all the time, all the options...

And still feel trapped if your mind isn't free.

I've watched founders hit 8 figures and feel less free than when they started.

Because they never learned this:

True freedom isn't escaping the game.

It's choosing which game to play.

And playing it on your terms.

These days?

 I work with people I respect
 I take Wednesdays off to think
 I turn down money that comes with strings
 I measure success by peace, not just profit

18 years taught me that freedom isn't about having no boss.

It's about being a boss worth working for.

Even when that boss is you.

Especially when that boss is you.

See you soon, Paris. Hello, Washington DC! 🇫🇷🇺🇸

Im excited to share that Ive officially graduated with a Masters in International Governance and Diplomacy from Sciences Po, ranked the 4th best university in the world for Politics!

I chose this program for a simple reason: after completing my Bachelors in International Business, with a specialization in Emerging Markets at Maastricht University School of Business and Economics, I realized I had built a strong foundation in economics and development. But something was missing. After reading Why Nations Fail, I understood that economic growth and prosperity are deeply tied to both economic and political institutions. I needed to complement my economic knowledge with a solid grasp of politics - and thats exactly what this program gave me.

This chapter also marks the end of my year-long internship at the OECD - OCDE, where I had the privilege of contributing to meaningful projects and flagship publications, including the Caribbean Development Dynamics 2025 and the Latin American Economic Outlook 2024.

To my family, friends, colleagues at the OECD, and professors in both Maastricht and Paris: thank you for your support, encouragement, and inspiration. Ive learned so much from each of you.

Now, Im thrilled to be moving to Washington DC to join the Inter-American Development Bank as a consultant in the Research Department. Ill be coordinating the Central Bank Adaptation to Climate Change Initiative and the Network of Central Banks and Finance Ministries, working directly with policymakers across Latin America and the Caribbean.

Excited for whats ahead!
